|  Sun to Make  Solaris More Linux Like                              |
|   from the imitation-is-the-sincerest-form-of-flattery dept.       |
|   posted by samzenpus on Thursday May 10, @00:46 (Sun Microsystems)|
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/10/030226            |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]ramboando writes "In an effort to spur adoption of Solaris, Sun
Microsystems has [1]begun a project code-named Indiana to try to give its
operating system some of Linux's success. Sun has been trying for years
to restore the luster of Solaris, but that since has faced a strong
challenge chiefly from Linux. Sun wants to embrace some Linux elements so
"we make Solaris a better Linux than Linux," said Ian Murdock, Sun's
chief operating systems officer, quoting Netscape co-founder Marc
Andreessen, whose latest start-up, Ning, uses Solaris. But it's a tricky
balance to adopt elements of Linux while preserving Solaris technology
and advantages such as the promise of backward compatibility. "As we make
Solaris more familiar to Linux users, we don't [want to] lose what makes
it more compelling and competitive.""

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/10/030226

